SENATE BILL 411
J1 6lr2317
CF HB 624
By: Senators Augustine, Hettleman, Kramer, and McCray
Introduced and read first time: January 29, 2026
Assigned to: Finance
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: March 23, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Hospitals – Clinical Staffing Committees and Plans – Establishment
3 (Safe Staffing Act of 2026)
4 FOR the purpose of requiring certain hospitals licensed in the State to comply with certain
5 staffing standards, to establish and maintain a clinical staffing committee, and to
6 implement a clinical staffing plan; requiring the chief nursing executive of each
7 hospital to produce a draft clinical staffing plan and submit it to the clinical staffing
8 committee of the hospital; requiring each clinical staffing committee to develop
9 finalize a clinical staffing plan; and generally relating to hospitals and clinical
10 staffing committees and plans.
11 BY adding to
12 Article – Health – General
13 Section 19–393 through 19–397 to be under the new part “Part XIII. Clinical Staffing
14 Committees and Plans”
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Health – General
20 19–391. RESERVED.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0411*

2 SENATE BILL 411
1 19–392. RESERVED.
2 PART XIII. CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEES AND PLANS.
3 19–393.
4 (A) IN THIS PART THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
5 INDICATED.
6 (B) (1) “ANCILLARY MEMBER OF THE FRONTLINE TEAM” MEANS AN
7 INDIVIDUAL WHOSE PRIMARY DUTIES INCLUDE SUPPORTING INDIVIDUALS WHO
8 PROVIDE DIRECT PATIENT CARE.
9 (2) “ANCILLARY MEMBER OF THE FRONTLINE TEAM” INCLUDES:
10 (I) A DIETARY WORKER;
11 (II) A PATIENT CARE TECHNICIAN; AND
12 (III) ANY OTHER NONLICENSED STAFF ASSISTING WITH PATIENT
13 CARE.
14 (C) “CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE” MEANS A COMMITTEE ESTABLISHED
15 BY A HOSPITAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION §
16 19–394(C) OF THIS SUBTITLE.
17 (D) (C) “CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN” MEANS A PLAN DEVELOPED UNDER
18 SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION § 19–394(D) OF THIS SUBTITLE.
19 19–394.
20 (A) THIS PART DOES NOT APPLY TO STATE HOSPITALS.
21 (B) (1) EACH HOSPITAL LICENSED UNDER THIS TITLE SHALL COMPLY
22 WITH THE STAFFING STANDARDS OF:
23 (I) THE ACCREDITATION BODY THAT ACCREDITS THE
24 HOSPITAL; AND
25 (II) THE FEDERAL CENTERS FOR MEDICARE AND MEDICAID
26 SERVICES CONDITIONS OF PARTICIPATION.
27 (2) A CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN DEVELOPED UNDER THIS PART
28 SHALL COMPLY WITH THIS SUBSECTION.

SENATE BILL 411 3
1 (C) (1) EACH HOSPITAL LICENSED UNDER THIS TITLE SHALL ESTABLISH
2 AND MAINTAIN A CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE THAT HAS EQUAL MEMBERSHIP
3 FROM MANAGEMENT AND EMPLOYEES:
4 (I) IF THE HOSPITAL HAS 150 OR FEWER LICENSED BEDS, HAS
5 3 MANAGERS AND 2 EMPLOYEES; OR
6 (II) IF THE HOSPITAL HAS 151 OR MORE LICENSED BEDS, HAS 5
7 MANAGERS AND 4 EMPLOYEES.
8 (2) EACH CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE ESTABLISHED UNDER
9 THIS PART SHALL MAY INCLUDE AT LEAST ONE OF THE FOLLOWING INDIVIDUALS:
10 (I) A CERTIFIED NURSING ASSISTANT;
11 (II) A DIETARY AIDE;
12 (III) AN EMERGENCY ROOM A LICENSED NURSE;
13 (IV) AN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WORKER;
14 (V) A MEDICAL RESIDENT, IF THE COMMITTEE IS IN A
15 TEACHING HOSPITAL;
16 (VI) A STAFF PHYSICIAN WHO IS NOT A HOSPITAL EMPLOYEE OR
17 ADMINISTRATOR; AND
18 (VII) A TECHNICIAN; OR
19 (VIII) AN EMPLOYEE WHOSE DUTIES INCLUDE PATIENT
20 ADVOCACY.
21 (3) A CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE ESTABLISHED UNDER
22 PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION MAY INCLUDE A PATIENT ADVOCATE.
23 (C) (D) (1) THE CHIEF NURSE EXECUTIVE OF EACH HOSPITAL SHALL
24 PRODUCE A DRAFT CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN AND SUBMIT IT TO THE CLINICAL
25 STAFFING COMMITTEE OF THE HOSPITAL.
26 (2) EACH CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE SHALL DEVELOP FINALIZE
27 A CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN THAT MEETS PATIENT NEEDS USING THE PLAN
28 SUBMITTED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION.

4 SENATE BILL 411
1 (D) (E) WHEN DEVELOPING FINALIZING A CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN, THE
2 CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE SHALL CONSIDER:
3 (1) EXISTING STAFFING LEVELS;
4 (2) METHODS TO SECURE COVERAGE NEEDS AS NECESSARY;
5 (3) EXISTING GAPS IN STAFFING AND HOW TO ADDRESS THE GAPS;
6 (4) ANY AVAILABLE EVIDENCE–BASED STAFFING STANDARDS; AND
7 (5) A SCHEDULE FOR PERIODIC REVIEW OF THE STAFFING PLAN;
8 (6) APPROPRIATE SKILL MIX AND COMPETENCY OF STAFF;
9 (7) STANDARDS REQUIRED BY:
10 (I) THE CENTERS FOR MEDICARE AND MEDICAID SERVICES
11 CONDITIONS OF PARTICIPATION; AND
12 (II) THE ACCREDITATION BODY THAT ACCREDITS THE
13 HOSPITAL;
14 (8) THE AVERAGE NUMBER OF PATIENTS OF THE HOSPITAL DURING
15 THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR AND RELEVANT INFORMATION REGARDING
16 PATIENT DISCHARGES, POTENTIAL ADMISSIONS, AND TRANSFERS;
17 (9) THE AVERAGE LEVEL OF ACUITY FOR PATIENTS OF THE HOSPITAL
18 DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR AND THE CORRESPONDING LEVEL OF
19 NURSING CARE REQUIRED; AND
20 (10) AN ESTIMATE OF THE APPROPRIATE COMBINATION OF SKILL,
21 EXPERIENCE LEVEL, AND SPECIALTY CERTIFICATION OR TRAINING OF STAFF THAT
22 IS REQUIRED TO ADEQUATELY PROVIDE CARE TO PATIENTS OF THE HOSPITAL.
23 (E) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1 EACH YEAR, EACH HOSPITAL, THROUGH THE
24 CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE, SHALL CONDUCT A REVIEW OF THE CLINICAL
25 STAFFING PLAN TO:
26 (1) EVALUATE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE CLINICAL STAFFING
27 PLAN DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR;
28 (2) UPDATE THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN TO ENSURE THAT THE
29 CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN CONTINUES TO BE APPROPRIATE AND EFFECTIVE; AND

SENATE BILL 411 5
1 (3) DEVELOP A PROCESS FOR RECEIVING, RESOLVING, AND
2 TRACKING COMPLAINTS RELATED TO THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN.
3 (F) IN DEVELOPING THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN, THE CLINICAL
4 STAFFING COMMITTEE SHALL CONSIDER:
5 (1) THE AVERAGE NUMBER OF PATIENTS ON EACH UNIT ON EACH
6 SHIFT DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR AND RELEVANT INFORMATION
7 REGARDING PATIENT DISCHARGES, POTENTIAL ADMISSIONS, AND TRANSFERS;
8 (2) THE AVERAGE LEVEL OF ACUITY FOR PATIENTS ON EACH UNIT ON
9 EACH SHIFT DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR AND THE
10 CORRESPONDING LEVEL OF NURSING CARE REQUIRED; AND
11 (3) AN ESTIMATE OF THE APPROPRIATE COMBINATION OF SKILL,
12 EXPERIENCE LEVEL, AND SPECIALTY CERTIFICATION OR TRAINING OF STAFF FOR
13 EACH UNIT ON EACH SHIFT THAT IS REQUIRED TO ADEQUATELY PROVIDE CARE.
14 19–395.
15 (A) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY JULY 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2028, EACH
16 HOSPITAL SHALL:
17 (1) IMPLEMENT THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN ADOPTED FINALIZED
18 UNDER § 19–394 OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
19 (2) ASSIGN PERSONNEL TO EACH PATIENT CARE UNIT IN
20 ACCORDANCE WITH THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN.
21 (B) A REGISTERED NURSE, A LICENSED PRACTICAL NURSE, AN ANCILLARY
22 MEMBER OF THE FRONTLINE TEAM, OR AN APPLICABLE EXCLUSIVE
23 REPRESENTATIVE MAY SUBMIT A COMPLAINT TO THE CLINICAL STAFFING
24 COMMITTEE REGARDING ANY VARIATION WHERE PERSONNEL ASSIGNMENT IN A
25 PATIENT CARE UNIT IS NOT IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ADOPTED CLINICAL
26 STAFFING PLAN.
27 (C) THE CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE SHALL DETERMINE, BY A
28 MAJORITY VOTE, WHETHER A COMPLAINT HAS BEEN ADEQUATELY RESOLVED.
29 19–396.
30 (A) SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION, ON OR BEFORE
31 JANUARY 1 EACH YEAR, EACH EACH HOSPITAL SHALL:

6 SENATE BILL 411
1 (1) POST IN A PUBLICLY ACCESSIBLE AND CONSPICUOUS AREA ON
2 EACH PATIENT UNIT THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN FOR THE UNIT AND THE ACTUAL
3 DAILY STAFFING FOR EACH SHIFT ON THE UNIT; AND
4 (2) ENSURE THAT A COPY OF THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN IS
5 AVAILABLE, ON REQUEST, ON EACH PATIENT UNIT PROVIDE THE CLINICAL
6 STAFFING PLAN TO STAFF ON REQUEST.
7 (B) IF A CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN FOR A UNIT IS AMENDED AFTER IT IS
8 IMPLEMENTED, THE HOSPITAL SHALL POST OR PROVIDE THE AMENDED CLINICAL
9 STAFFING PLAN FOR THE UNIT IN THE MANNER REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (A)
10 OF THIS SECTION IN A TIMELY MANNER.
11 19–397.
12 (A) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2030, EACH
13 HOSPITAL LICENSED UNDER THIS TITLE SHALL SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE
14 MARYLAND HEALTH CARE COMMISSION SUMMARIZING HOW THE HOSPITAL’S
15 CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE HAS ADDRESSED SAFE HOSPITAL STAFFING
16 THROUGH THE HOSPITAL’S CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN DURING THE IMMEDIATELY
17 PRECEDING YEAR.
18 (B) THE MARYLAND HEALTH CARE COMMISSION SHALL:
19 (1) COMPILE THE REPORTS SUBMITTED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF
20 THIS SECTION; AND
21 (2) MAKE THE COMPILED REPORT PUBLICLY AVAILABLE BY
22 PUBLISHING THE COMPILATION ON THE MAIN PAGE OF ITS WEBSITE.
23 THIS PART MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED TO REQUIRE A HOSPITAL TO TAKE
24 ACTIONS THAT ARE INCONSISTENT WITH THE CENTERS FOR MEDICARE AND
25 MEDICAID SERVICES CONDITIONS OF PARTICIPATION OR THE ACCREDITATION
26 STANDARDS OF THE ACCREDITATION BODY THAT ACCREDITS THE HOSPITAL.
27 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That each hospital shall establish
28 a clinical staffing committee as required under § 19–394 of the Health – General Article,
29 as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, on or before January July 1, 2027.
30 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That each clinical staffing
31 committee hospital shall develop implement a clinical staffing plan as required under §
32 19–394 of the Health – General Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, on or before
33 July 1, 2027 2028.

SENATE BILL 411 7
1 SECTION 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
2 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
